It was published in a long time ago, back before Tenex. 
Here are some citations:

Peter J Denning, "Virtual Memory" ACM Computing Surveys 2,  No 2, 
March-April p 111-114

Denning and Tichy, 1991, "Operating Systems," in _Encyclopedia of
Computer Science_ Van Norstrand Reinhold

Denning, "Working sets, past and present" IEEE Transactions on
Software Engineering SE-6, No 1 (January) p 64-84

 It was also described in several texts on
operating systems, including Denning's.

I never, personally, saw the proof that is is optimal, but when I was
studying Operating Systems with Denning, he talked about it. He said
that a few years after his work, another paper compared the emperical
results using working sets against a theoritical optimal system that
knew what pages would be needed, and in what order. The paper showed
that you could get very close to the impossible "theoritical optimal"
(about 4% worse) using proper working set tuning. I could find the
cite, by asking Peter, if there is lots of interest.

The LRU approach that way too many systems use is not close to
optimal, and requires far too much manual tuning to get even decent
balance. I haven't seen a lot of detail for other OS approaches, but I
spent far too much time understanding VMS'. bletch. 

What is truely sad is that Denning's virtual memory had a great 
track record on Tenex/Tops-20 systems, yet Cutler and the PDP-11
folks paid no attention to it when they built the Vax. Worse still,
IMHO, is that he apparently didn't even do it right on NT. I can
forgive a mistake that is nearly 20 years old, but someone should have
learned in the years since.

One of the things that amazed me when I was a graduate teaching
assistant for Denning's Operating Systems class was that of the
students, that hadn't been completely mindzapped thinking that MS-DOS
was the only operating system, could not even imagine that with
working sets, the system tunes the sizes automatically rather than
requiring a sys-admin to set quotas and limits.

Pat
