LOTS stood for "Low Overhead TimeSharing", which referred to the
staffing, not the quality of service.  It was founded in the late 70's
by Ralph Gorin (now of XKL?) and John McCarthy.  Ralph served as its
first full-time manager.  FTE staff was 3.5 when I was there (.5 time
Director, FT manager, FT systems programmer, FT administrative
assistant), with loads of help provided by students and other Stanford
facilities.

LOTS ran Stanford-modified TOPS-20 (on a 2040, at first, which was
upgraded to a 2050 and augmented by a 2050 in 1981-2).  Typical heavy
user load on each machine was in the neighborhood of 100-120 users.

We had a user community of about 6,000 total.  It was a fun place to work.

Bob
