At it's peak, LOTS was *THREE* pretty vanilla TOPS-20 systems (w/CFS), a
backup/devlopment machine, and a Systems Concept SC-30M.  "Pretty vanilla"
is relative, Stanford being one of the sites that did a fair amount of
monitor, exec, and utility development, but a lot of those were general
enough to get folded back in by DEC (eventually), and there wasn't anything
that would stop anyone from calling it tops20.  I don't think it ever hit
1000 simultaneous users (for the cluster), but it certainly got up to "too
many"...

There was a vax or two and an IBM mini-mainframe, too, but they didn't
really count.

Sadly, the LOTS (Low Overhead Timesharing, where you get students and
volunteers to do a lot of the work that is normally necessary to support
a mainframe computer facility) philosophy gave way to the "microcomputers
need no support at all" philosophy, and any interesting applications or
systems modifications that might get developed simply dissappear when
the next student boots the machine, instead of surviving for all.
(And of course, the size of the organization supporting the "no support"
computers is much larger than the size of the old LOTS stafff :-)

A fair number of the last of the LOTS crew ended up at XKL, and I suspect
that Rich, at least, will say more.  I was merely on the periphery
(occasionally using the development machine for development.)

BillW



