>What's wrong with paper tape?

(If Tim Shoppa hadn't replied to your question, I would have never seen
it; this software often skips messages and I haven't determined why.)

Paper tape was very clumsy to use.  I will tell  you how Digital used to
do their development cycles on the smaller machines (read that not
PDP-10s; they did things the right way [smiley face here showing its
prejudice).  A programmer would code by writing on coding paper.  He
(there were no shes) would then submit the hand-written code to Tape Prep.
 Tape Prep would then type it off-line on a KSR-35 transferring the
hand-written to oil paper tape.  Now note that this oil paper tape (when
the typing job was finished) could be 50-100' long.  The tape was then
read on the KSR-35 reader, producing a listing which could be proofed. 
Errors were marked up and edited (use your imagination about how one goes
about editing a 50' oiled paper tape).  When all edits were made and the
paper tape reflected what the programmer wanted,  the oil paper tape was
then copied to fan-fold.  If the programmer wanted an assembly done, this
fan-fold paper tape was taken to System 40 (a PDP-10, remember that
system, guys?), read in with the paper tape reader to disk [sigh,
finally].  Then the code was assembled with all its errors, a listing
produced, etc. with the appropriate cross-assembler.  If the programmer
wanted his stuff on DECtape (the best media ever invented in the whole
wide world), it was copied using FILEX.

B.T.W., when I got in charge of the RUNOFF group in Tape Prep.  Those
KSR-35 procedures became history fast.  Everyone got their own PPN and
everything was entered on-line.  If the programmer wanted a paper tape, we
produced one, but it was a rare request.  Everybody wanted stuff on
DECtape.

Now, if you had a 50' paper tape, and you dropped it, it was a mess. 
Reading 50' of fanfold in the -10's paper tape reader was an art that
required acrobatic skills. I would have much rather handled cards.

/BAH


