Here are the capacities (in mbytes) for various DEC drives that were also
connectable to systems whose word lengths divide by 6 rather than 8,
according to this book:

Model    Type            Platters   Size MB  Access Time  Xfer Rate  Rot. Speed
-----    ----------      --------   -------  -----------  ---------  ----------
RK05     Rem. cartridge    1           1.2      70 ms     1.1us/word  1500 rpm
RL01     Rem. cartridge    1           5.2      55 ms     512KB/sec   2400
RM03     Rem. disk pack    5          67        38 ms     1.2MB/sec   3600
RP04/5   Rem. disk pack   10          88        36 ms     806KB/sec   3600
RP06     Rem. disk pack   10         176        36 ms     806KB/sec   3600
RP07     Fixed Winchester  9         516        31.3 ms   1.3MB/2.2MB* 3633
RA60     Rem. disk pack    5         205        50        1.98MB/sec  3600
RA81     Fixed Winchester  4         456        36.3      2.2MB/sec   3600

* 1.3 MB/sec in brain-dead VAX mode; RP07-D (for 36-bits) did 2.2MB/sec. 
One of the fastest drives Digital sold during the 36-bit era; not matched
until the RA81.  Of course, the RA81's speed was mitigated by all the
extra latency added by going through an HSC.

