You answered your question.  You only had 256KW of memory.  Even in the
early days, the operating system and its data structures were pretty close
to 256K (about 128K or so of which needed to be resident).  We're talking
*major* thrash opportunity here.  DEC once sold 128K machines as bottom of
the line systems, but those were completely unusable and eventually even
the OS punted on trying to support them.

You can especially see this on a 2020.  A 256KW 2020 is slow; a 512KW 2020
makes a nice single-user machine.

Of course, if you had CS types running lots of TeX and (shudder!) LISP
jobs, you really needed a 4MW machine...

The PDP-11 did not do swapping.  The PDP-11 handled the terminals.

