I worked in PDP-10 Engineering for 2 years starting JUN68. TOPS-10 was small in
those days. The development machine, KA10 #2, had 32KW. One day in '69
several engineers went to the cafeteria just before 1PM and joined several
programmers who were already in a lunchroom discussion.

One programmer said, "Here's a few users. Let's ask them." He then described a
new feature they had just put in the OS. We said it sounds good, what's the
issue? We were told it takes 3 words of resident core. In '69 this was suitable
for lunchroom discussion.

Some of you remember W102s were hard to come by. The development team wanted a
third bank of memory on #2. Manufacturing had lots of core stacks but no W102s.
Tom Eggers noticed the two banks of memory on #2 each had 3 memory ports
populated with W102s. Only 2 ports were being used. They got a third memory bank
sans W102s from manufacturing, populated two ports, and upgraded #2 to 48KW WITH
NO ADDITIONAL USERS. Needless to say the OS started growing.

The previous LOTS discussion pointed out that it wasn't long before TOPS-20
wouldn't boot on 128K:

