As a student at Dundee University in 1981 we had a DEC-10 connected via
ANF-10 to several other machines including a DEC-10 at Edinburgh University.
At one point Dundee University upgraded to (and my version number
memory is hazy now but roughly) TOPS-10 7 something while Edinburgh were
still at 6 something. Previously TOPS-10 had attempted to assign all DN87(?)
lines to itself and leave them connected but now Dundee would disconnect
them at the end of a session ("HOST SENT DISCONNECT") and they would be grabbed by
Edinburgh. Result was that hundreds of network unware students would find
themselves fruitlessly trying to login to a machine 50 miles away at the end of a
low speed link. Eventually Dundee patched the DN87 code to prevent it from
attaching terminals to anything other than their own machines.

