I *think* that the reason that this idea didn't fly when we first
thought about it (the quest for less powerhungry disk having been 
a long and ongoing saga) goes like this...

The KS10 uses the RH11C version of the traditional RH11 massbuss 
controller.  This is meaningful because it does not do 16 bits+2 parity,
but instead does 18 bits + no parity.  Being a 36 bit machine, 18 is good,
16 is bad.  The RM03 and RP06 (and RP07 and RM80) were able to fake this
18bit world as well, though some of them (RP07?) needed to have special
HDAs.  Man, all of this is fuzzy now...

So, what you might have luck doing is taking the mass buss adapter out 
of an RM03 and hooking the 2322 or other fuji spinning storage up to 
that; I am not sure if they did funny things to the device IDs although
I get a feeling now that I think on it that they did...  There was some 
issue with the number of sectors, etc. too.   I think that after the 
MBA in the drive is the closest that things come to being "standard" in 
this chain of events, and thus the easiest to fake it, but your mileage
may vary, as they say.  

If you really want to have fun, now that RAM prices are getting so low
you could build a ramdisk for it and really let it fly ;-)  Of course,
going from 2901 to 29203 super-slice bit slice processors might also help
things, but then we are into microcode hackery and we have lives now, and 
dave moon no doubt has other things to do...  Reality intrudes.

One thing that MIGHT have more promise is to realize exactly how low
performance those ooriginal drives were, and see if you could take a 
machine, say a unix box or whatever weapon you feel you wield the best,
and put that disk channel onto a parallel port on that thing (if you can 
get a port that will do 18 bits ;-) and write some tight code that will 
see the requests come down the line, and go fetch the right thing from 
disk.  With even general purpose machines flying at mach 6 these days, 
might one of them be able to perform the tasks that we used to have to 
do with really specialized hardware playing smart disk controllers?
That way, you can put disk on the machine at a price of a grand per 
gig or even MUCH less.

Doug



