The Emulex SC1x series only know how to work in "16-bit" mode, and
don't work in "18-bit" mode.  I think they may fake a few 18-bit
operations to satisfy some of the PDP-11 diagnostics, but the 
structure on disk is 16-bit words only.

There are also considerations about the differences between "real"
Massbus device registers and the "emulated" Massbus device registers
on the Emulex SC1x-type interfaces.  For example, the SC1x series
works fine on a Unibus PDP-11 and looks like a Massbus device to the
OS, but it doesn't work right if you pop it into the Unibus of a
VAX 11/780.  This is because the Massbus adapter on a 11/780 doesn't
live at all in Unibus address space - the Massbus adapters hang differently
from the SBI (I believe the original terminology is that they are on
a different "nexus".)

On the other hand, RP's and RM's are very SMD-like inside.  There
are supposedly a few inverted signals to screw you over if you try
this, but you could replace, say, the RM03 drive with a 2322 and keep
the SMD-ish to massbus boards which are in the pedestal.  If you're
really interested in this option, I believe I have print sets for
both the DEC RM03 and the CDC drive it was based on (9762?  Serious
brain fade going on here.)

Didn't System Concepts make 18-bit SMD to Massbus adapters?  Or
was that (shudder) System Industries?

