If you're going to write your own drivers, I'd just find a unused
parallel port (or build one) and hook up an IDE drive.  It'll require
a couple of chips of TTL in between, but the interface is trivial:
an IDE drive is just a set of registers.  Of course, any DMA support
would be up to you to design - most all IDE drives work through
programmed I/O on PC-clones.  No IDE drives that I know of support
non-8-bit words, but as long as you're working around the lack of DMA,
this is trivial in comparison.

>Side question: Did the MASSBUSS on the 11/70 live partially on the UBA? Just 
>curious if one programmed it by twiddling the bits on the Unibus, and then 
>sitting back while the 32Bit Massbuss Direct Cache//Memory interface sucked 
>your data in like a hoover...

That's exactly how it works.  All the drive and control registers appeared
on Unibus connectors in the Massbus slots.

>The big problem here is I'd have to use a HDA that precicely matched a RM02 
>drive (what was it: 677 cyls, 5 heads, 30s/t?). Giving me a piddly 70Mb of 
>disk space (well, those are 16 bit words). Per power sucking, noisy 
>controller... Not too high a ROI...

The Fujitsu 2321 is a pretty good match for that.  You'd have to set
the sector length properly for 18-bit words, but that's absolutely
straightforward.

>But then there is the RM05. 256 Mb with a geometry that might be matchable. 

The hard part matching this will be finding a drive with a slow enough
data rate.  The more modern SMD drives of this capacity or bigger (in
particular the Fujitsu 2351A, 2361, 2333, 2334, 2344, etc.) which are
readily available on the surplus market have higher data rates.  You
could probably put in a Fujitsu 2284-series drive, and while this is
an improvement over a RM05, it's still a 150 pound 14-inch disk drive.
And they aren't as reliable as the later Fujitsu drives, so you're
less likely to find them in working condition.  They were late enough
that they had a lot of custom Fujitsu MSI chips in them, making repair
a bit more difficunt than the RM05-era drives.  

