    Back in '69 when I worked in PDP-10 engineering a few of
us used to play bridge and run to the cafeteria at 12:55 just
before it closed.
    One day we joined some TOPS-10 programmers who were talking
shop over lunch. One of them said, "Here's some users; let's
ask them." He then described some new feature they had just
added to the monitor on the development system, KA10 #2.
    One of us said, "Sounds good. What's the issue?"
    The reply, "It takes three words of resident code."
    It's been a long time since increasing the size of a
monitor by 3 words was suitable for a lunch time shop
discussion. It's also been a long time since the list price
of 3 words of memory was $9.16.
    Back then MA10 memory cost $50K for 16K words (80K x
8-bits) or $0.61/byte or $640K/Mbyte vs. ~$11/Mbyte today.
